ould segfault.\n\nLet me also check `trim_string` with empty input:\n- `len == 0` case: after `trim_string`, `len == 0` and `clean_s` is returned. Back in main, `if (len == 0) { free(s); ... }`. `s` is the original pointer, and `free(s)` is correct. ✅\n\n**Another potential issue:** In the loop, if `get_string` returns a very long string (e.g., 10000 chars), `realloc` inside `get_string` will be called log2(10000) ≈ 14 times. That's generally fine, but it's worth noting that `get_string` uses an inline function with `malloc`/`realloc` inside a tight loop. For this program's purposes, performance is not an issue.\n\n**Let me also check `trim_string` behavior with NULL input:**\nIf `get_string` returns NULL (failed malloc/realloc), then `s` is NULL and `len` is -1. Then:\n- `len == -1 && ferror(stdin)` — `ferror(stdin)` would be... well, if malloc/realloc failed, it doesn't set `ferror`. So we'd enter the `len == -1` check (line 67), try to `free(NULL)` → no-op, break. This is actually fine! Wait, would `s` be NULL? Yes, `get_string` returns NULL on failure. And `free(NULL)` is defined as no-op. So the code would actually handle this gracefully.\n\n   But wait, `len == -1` is set by `get_string` on EOF (when `getchar()` returns EOF), AND on `realloc` failure (where `*len = -1` and returns NULL). These are two different conditions with the same `len == -1`. If `get_string` returns NULL due to allocation failure, we enter the `ferror(stdin)` check — but stdin's error flag is NOT set by an allocation failure (that's a C library internal). So we'd enter the clean EOF branch (line 67), `free(NULL)` → no-op, `break`. This subtly treats an allocation failure as EOF, which is wrong but harmless (no crash, just stops reading prematurely).\n\n   This is a very corner case — a system so memory-constrained that `realloc` of 1 byte fails is basically unusable. But it's worth noting as a theoretical hole.\n\nOK let me also think about one more thing: the diagnostic style. According to § 4.6:\n\n> Сообщение об ошибке — конкретика, не штамп: что не получилось, какое значение получено, какое допустимо.\n\nThe error messages currently say:\n- Line 20: \"Радиус не задан; нет аргументов или пустой аргумент\" — OK, tells what's missing\n- Line 25: \"Радиус не задан; слишком много аргументов\" — OK\n- Line 32: \"Радиус должен быть числом. Получено: %s\" — tells what was received, good\n- Line 37: \"Радиус должен быть конечным числом. Получено: %s\" — OK\n- Line 42: \"Радиус должен быть положительным. Получено: %.3f\" — OK, tells value received\n- Line 92: \"Строка %d. Некорректные данные: %s\" — tells line number and what was received, could also specify what was expected (3 numbers X Y Z)\n- Line 101: \"Строка %d. Ожидалось X Y Z, получено: %s\" — good, tells expectation and what was received\n\nThe error message on line 92 could be more specific: \"Строка %d. Ожидалось X Y Z, получено: %s\" — same as line 101, actually. Let me compare the two error cases:\n- Line 91: `*end != ' ' && *end != '\\0'` → \"Некорректные данные\" — this catches non-numeric garbage in place of a coordinate\n- Line 100: `*end == '\\0' && j != 2` → \"Ожидалось X Y Z\" — this catches premature end of line\n\nThese are correctly differentiated. Good.\n\nOK, let me summarize the key findings for the user:\n\n**Critical (could crash):**\n1. **Line 52: `malloc` without NULL check** — если `malloc` сразу не удался, `points[sz] = ...` на строке 116 упадёт. Надо `if (!points) { fprintf(stderr, ...); return io_fail; }`.\n\n**Minor bugs / anti-patterns:**\n2. **setlocale не вызван** — сейчас работает (strtod в C-локали понимает точки). Если добавить `setlocale(LC_ALL, \"Russian_Russia.1251\")`, `strtod` сломается (будет ждать запятую). Нужно либо решение с `LC_NUMERIC`, либо осознанно не ставить.\n3. **`strtod` парсит пустой `argv[1]` как 0.0** — `main.exe \"\"` провалится в `r <= 0`, а не в \"не число\". Мелочь, но несоответствие C++-версии.\n\n**Style:**\n4. `malloc(sizeof(struct Po